# agentBrowser

Minimal Chrome controller for AI agents — CDP over Node.js, wrapped as a pip-installable Python library.

Controls a real visible Chrome window. Thread-safe: each thread automatically gets its own Chrome port, profile directory, and state, so parallel agents never share a tab or interfere with each other's clicks.

**Requires:** Python 3.11+, Node.js 22+, Google Chrome

---

## Installation

```bash
# From local path
pip install -e C:/path/to/agentBrowser

# From git
pip install git+https://github.com/yourname/agentBrowser.git
```

---

## Python API

```python
import agent_browser as ab

# Navigate — returns snapshot with @ref IDs for every interactive element
result = ab.navigate("https://example.com")
# result = {
#   "success": True,
#   "url": "https://example.com",
#   "snapshot": "- link \"About\" [ref=e1, url=...]\n- button \"Sign in\" [ref=e2]\n...",
#   "refs": {"e1": {"role": "link", "name": "About", ...}, ...}
# }

# Refresh snapshot after a click or page change
snap = ab.snapshot()

# Interact using @ref IDs from the snapshot
ab.click("e2")           # or ab.click("@e2")
ab.type_text("hello")    # types into currently focused element
ab.press_key("Enter")    # key names: Enter, Tab, Escape, ArrowDown, ...
ab.scroll("down", 600)   # scroll down 600px
ab.back()                # browser history back

# Close this thread's Chrome instance when done
ab.close_browser()
```

### One-shot search helpers

Skip the navigate → find search box → click → type → submit flow:

```python
ab.google_search("machine learning papers 2024")
ab.bing_search("site:github.com pytorch examples")
ab.baidu_search("人工智能最新论文")
ab.reddit_search("best async Python libraries")
```

Each returns the same dict as `navigate()`.

---

## Agent framework integration

`agent_browser.tools` provides OpenAI-compatible tool definitions and a `dispatch()` function so you can plug directly into any LLM tool-calling loop:

```python
from agent_browser.tools import TOOL_DEFINITIONS, dispatch
from openai import OpenAI
import json

client = OpenAI()
messages = [{"role": "user", "content": "Search Google for recent LLM papers and tell me the top results"}]

while True:
    response = client.chat.completions.create(
        model="gpt-4o-mini",
        messages=messages,
        tools=TOOL_DEFINITIONS,
    )
    msg = response.choices[0].message
    messages.append(msg)

    if not msg.tool_calls:
        print(msg.content)
        break

    for tc in msg.tool_calls:
        args = json.loads(tc.function.arguments)
        result = dispatch(tc.function.name, args)   # returns JSON string
        messages.append({
            "role": "tool",
            "tool_call_id": tc.id,
            "content": result,
        })
```

Available tools (12): `browser_navigate`, `browser_snapshot`, `browser_click`, `browser_type`, `browser_press_key`, `browser_scroll`, `browser_back`, `browser_close`, `google_search`, `bing_search`, `baidu_search`, `reddit_search`

---

## Profile setup (cookies / login state)

By default each Chrome instance starts fresh. To give agents your login sessions:

**Option A — Import cookies from your existing Chrome profile** (run with Chrome closed):

```bash
python -m agent_browser setup-profile
# or: agent-browser setup-profile

# To use a specific Chrome profile instead of auto-detecting:
python -m agent_browser setup-profile "Profile 2"
```

**Option B — Log in manually inside an agent-managed Chrome window:**

```bash
python -m agent_browser login
# or: agent-browser login
```

This opens Chrome with the agent profile. Log in to whatever sites you need, then close Chrome. Cookies are saved automatically.

**How the profile is used at runtime:**

```
~/.agentbrowser/profiles/
  shared/          ← your cookies/sessions (written by setup-profile or login)
  run_<PID>/       ← per-run scratch copy of shared (created at agent startup)
  <PID>_t1/        ← per-thread copy for worker thread 1
  <PID>_t2/        ← per-thread copy for worker thread 2
  ...
```

Each run and each thread gets its own copy, so a crashed agent never corrupts the shared profile, and parallel threads never share a Chrome session.

To check what's configured:

```bash
python -m agent_browser info
```

---

## Parallel use

Each Python thread automatically gets a unique Chrome port and profile. No configuration needed:

```python
from concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor
import agent_browser as ab

def scrape(url: str) -> str:
    result = ab.navigate(url)
    # ... ab.click(), ab.snapshot(), etc.
    # Each thread controls its own Chrome tab with its own cookies
    ab.close_browser()
    return result["snapshot"]

urls = ["https://example.com", "https://github.com", "https://arxiv.org"]
with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=len(urls)) as pool:
    snapshots = list(pool.map(scrape, urls))
```

Port layout: `base = 9222 + (PID % 100) * 10`. Thread 0 → base, thread 1 → base+1, etc. (10 slots per process, 100 process slots before wrapping). Override the base with `AGENT_BROWSER_PORT`.

---

## Environment variables

| Variable | Default | Description |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `AGENT_BROWSER_PORT` | `9222 + (PID%100)*10` | Port base for this process; each thread adds its slot index |
| `AGENT_BROWSER_PROFILES_DIR` | `~/.agentbrowser/profiles` | Root directory for all managed profiles |
| `AGENT_BROWSER_PROFILE` | set automatically | Profile subdirectory name; set by `ensure_browser_profile()` |
| `AGENT_BROWSER_STATE_DIR` | set per-thread | Per-thread dir for `session.json` and `refs.json`; set automatically |
| `CHROME_PATH` | auto-detect | Override the Chrome executable path |

---

## Node.js CLI

The underlying CLI can be used standalone without Python:

```bash
node src/cli.js start                         # launch Chrome on port 9222
node src/cli.js open https://example.com      # navigate
node src/cli.js snapshot --json               # dump interactive elements as JSON
node src/cli.js click @e1                     # click by @ref
node src/cli.js keyboard type "search query"  # type text
node src/cli.js keyboard press Enter          # press a key
node src/cli.js scroll down 800              # scroll
node src/cli.js back                          # navigate back
node src/cli.js close                         # close Chrome
node src/cli.js screenshot page.png           # take screenshot
```

Same env vars apply: `AGENT_BROWSER_PORT`, `AGENT_BROWSER_STATE_DIR`, `AGENT_BROWSER_PROFILES_DIR`, `AGENT_BROWSER_PROFILE`, `CHROME_PATH`.

